# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fusil-gras-mle-1874
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The **11×59mmR Gras**, also known as the **11mm Vickers**, is a rifle cartridge.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] France's first modern military cartridge, the 11×59mmR Gras was introduced in 1874 and continued in service in various roles and with various users until after World War II.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The 11×59mmR was a rimmed, slightly bottlenecked, centerfire rifle cartridge with an external Berdan primer, developed for use in the single shot, bolt actioned Fusil Gras mle 1874.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The original 1874 cartridge fired a paper patched, 25.0 g (386 gr), 27 mm (1.06 in) long lead bullet driven by 5.2 g (81 gr) of F1 black powder, with a muzzle velocity of 450 m/s (1,500 ft/s), the velocity dropping to 430 m/s (1,400 ft/s) at 25 m (82 ft).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] An improved cartridge was introduced in 1879 with a slower burning F3 powder, alterations to the tip of the bullet and a reduction in the height of the patch.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] In 1884 a bullet was introduced of 5% antimony and 95% lead which was compressed and hardened instead of simply cast, and the tip was flattened to improve accuracy.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] During World War I an incendiary round was manufactured to be fired from the cartridge for the balloon busting role.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The Remington Rolling Block rifle was also chambered in the 11×59mmR Gras cartridge.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The 11×59mmR Gras was used extensively in both the Remington and the Gras rifles by Japan, Chile, Ethiopia, a number of Balkan states, and France's North African colonial possessions.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] Greece initially chambered their Mylonas rifle in this cartridge but later adopted the Fusil Gras mle 1874 as their standard rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] In 1886 it was replaced in French frontline service by the revolutionary 8×50mmR Lebel, the first military cartridge to use smokeless gunpowder.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The Lebel cartridge was itself created by necking down the 11×59mmR.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] Despite being superseded, the Gras rifle and the 11×59mmR cartridge continued in wide service with territorial and second-line troops as well as throughout France's colonies, continuing in these roles during the Great War.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] In 1916 it was decided to re-equip the Kingdom of Serbia's Army with French-made weapons, and from October of that year, the Serbian Army received 20,000 Gras rifles along with other French weapons.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] Due to a chronic shortage of modern rifles within the Imperial Russian Army, 105,000 Gras rifles and a quantity of 11×59mmR cartridges were supplied to Russia during the war, these rifles were subsequently used by the Red Army in their early years.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] By 1917 it had been determined that standard rifle calibre cartridges were less satisfactory for balloon busting (shooting down observation balloons) than larger calibres carrying incendiary or tracer bullets.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The French adapted the standard 11×59mmR Gras cartridge to fire from their Hotchkiss M1914 machine gun as an aircraft gun.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The Vickers aircraft machine gun and the 11mm Vickers was adopted by the allies as a standard anti-balloon armament and used by both the British and French in this role until the end of the war, as well as other allies such as Belgium and the United States of America.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] Notable users include Belgium's leading fighter ace and the allies' champion balloon buster Willy Coppens, and America's two highest scoring fighter aces, Eddie Rickenbacker and Frank Luke.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] In the late 1930s, remaining Mauser-Koka 1884 artillery carbines within the Yugoslav inventory were converted from the 10.15×63mmR Mauser to 11×59mmR Gras cartridges which were in good supply in Yugoslav Army depots.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] During the Spanish Civil War a number of Republican troops were armed with Gras rifles.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-59mmr-gras] The last known official user of the 11×59mmR was Yemen, who continued to use the Gras rifle and cartridge into the 1950s.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] The **11mm Mauser** (also known as the 11×60mmR Mauser or .43 Mauser) is a black-powder cartridge developed between 1867 and 1871 and used in the Mauser Model 1871 rifle, as well as the 71/84 variant.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] It was popular in German sporting rifles up until the early 20th century.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] It is no longer in production, however it is available from custom loaders and handloading can be done.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] As early as 1867, the first considerations arose in Prussia to replace the needle rifle with a breech-loading weapon with centerfire cartridges.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] On November 7, 1871, the Prussian Rifle Commission set the caliber of the new rifle at 11 mm.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] The cartridge is based on the Werder rifle cartridge, caliber 11 × 50 mm R.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/11-60mm-mauser] In 1904, a German gunsmith from Suhl, August Schüler, developed a rimless version of the cartridge to be used in Gewehr 88 & Gewehr 98 actions.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The **8×50mmR Lebel** (8mm Lebel) (designated as the **8 × 51 R Lebel** by the C.I.P.) rifle cartridge was the first smokeless powder cartridge to be made and adopted by any country.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11×59mmR Gras black powder cartridge, the smokeless 8mm Lebel cartridge started a revolution in military rifle ammunition.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Standard 8mm Lebel military ammunition was also the first rifle ammunition to feature a spitzer boat tail bullet (*balle* D), which was adopted in 1898.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The long-range ballistic performance of the 8mm Lebel bullet itself was exceptional for its time.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] For use in the magazine tube-fed early Lebel rifle, the 8 mm case was designed to protect against accidental percussion inside the tube magazine by a circular groove around the primer cup which caught the tip of the following pointed bullet.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] However, the shape of its rimmed bottle-necked case, having been designed for the Lebel rifle's tube magazine, also precluded truly efficient vertical stacking inside a vertical magazine.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The bolt thrust of the 8mm Lebel is relatively high compared to many other service rounds used in the early 20th century.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Although it was once revolutionary, the 8mm Lebel was declared obsolete after World War I and was soon after replaced with the 7.5×54mm French round.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] There were two historical commercially available 8mm Lebel cartridges: one for the Lebel Model 1886 rifle, and one for the Modèle 1892 revolver.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] They are two entirely different cartridges and are not interchangeable.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The term "8mm Lebel" for the French Mle 1892 revolver ammunition, is only applied outside France for commercial reasons and has nothing to do with the Lebel rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] However, the term "8mm Lebel", used to identify a rifle cartridge, is widely recognized to distinguish the French rifle cartridge from other 8 mm rifle cartridges, such as the 8×50mmR Mannlicher cartridge used by Austria-Hungary and its successor states.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The cartridge for the tube-fed long arm was originally loaded with a 15.0 g (232 grains) cupro-nickel-jacketed, lead-cored, flat-nosed, wadcutter-style bullet, called "*balle M*", which had been designed by Lieutenant Colonel Nicolas Lebel.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The flat point (flat nose or tip) of this bullet had been designed to be safe inside the newly commissioned rifle's tube magazine.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] It was propelled by the first practical smokeless, nitrocellulose-based powder (*Poudre B*), as developed by Paul Vieille in 1884.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The ballistic performance and range of *balle M* with the new propellant eclipsed all the previous military ammunitions in existence at the time (1886).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] This *balle M* was replaced in 1898 by a new design, a 12.8 g (198 grains) 90/10 bronze mono-metal, pointed (spitzer) boat-tail bullet called "*balle D*", which provided a flatter trajectory and improved long-range performance.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Designed at the Atelier de Puteaux (APX) by Captain Georges Desaleux, the *balle D* was the first pointed *and* boat-tailed bullet to be placed into service by any military.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Later on in 1912, the round was improved into the *balle D am* ("am" stands for "*amorçage modifié*" or "modified primer"), done by crimping the primer in more deeply to prevent primer expulsions when fired in machine guns.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] This ammunition was in near-universal service during World War I (1914–1918) in all Lebel-caliber weapons.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The *balle D am* ammunition was followed in 1932 by *balle N* ammunition, which featured a lead-cored, cupro-nickel-over-steel-jacketed, pointed boat-tail bullet weighing 15.0 g (232 grains).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] It was thicker (8.3 mm instead of 8.17) and was held into a case that had a slightly larger neck diameter than that for the older *balle D am* ammunition.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The new *balle N* was again heavier than the *balle D am*, and had been designed to improve the long-range performance of the issued Hotchkiss machine guns.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Rechambering practically all French Lebel-caliber rifles and carbines to use the "N"-type ammunition was carried out during the 1930s.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] A *balle T* (tracer ammunition) and *balle P* armor-piercing rounds were also produced, along with blank and reduced charge cartridges.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] In order to safely accommodate pointed (spitzer) bullets inside the Lebel rifle magazine, a circular groove was machined around each primer cup at the case base on both *balle D am* and *balle N* ammunitions.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The role of that circular groove is to receive the pointed bullet tip of the following round loaded inside the tube magazine, and keep it *at the side* of the case base of the previous cartridge, so the tip does not easily slide to the base center where the primer is located.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The tapered form of the case itself did help too to keep pointed tips away from the primer cup of a round in front of another in the tube.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Furthermore, all *balle D* and *balle M* French military ammunitions featured *convex primer covers* which are crimped in over the primer itself.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Those small covers are not noticeable, but do provide a second effective protection against accidental primer percussion inside the Lebel's tube magazine.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Wartime experiences (1914–1918) involving hundreds of millions of Lebel rounds fired in combat have entirely confirmed the effectiveness of these protections.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] While revolutionary for its time in terms of ballistic performance, the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge had its drawbacks.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11mm Gras rifle cartridge case, it was an odd design, with a thick rim and a rapid double taper.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] This made it more difficult to feed from standard magazine firearms such as the Berthier rifles and the Chauchat machine guns, and is the reason for the distinct curvature in the magazines of those firearms.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The Lebel rifle from which it was fired was also rather outdated by the time *balle D*, let alone the *balle N*, came along.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] A *balle N* round can only be fired from Lebel or Berthier rifles, if the chamber has been reamed to accept the larger neck of the N-type cartridge.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Such weapons are stamped *N* on top of the barrel, just in front of the receiver and behind the rear sight.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The *balle N* ammunition is identifiable by the fact that the bullet, while pointed like the solid-brass *balle D*, is lead-cored and jacketed with soft steel.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] While newly manufactured 8×50mmR Lebel ammunition has become available in the U.S., reloadable cartridge cases can also be produced by reforming .348 Winchester brass.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The 8mm Lebel round produced by Prvi Partizan is of excellent quality and replicates the performance of the original round.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] However, Privi Partizan's *older style* brass cases lack the circular groove around the primer cup, so reloaders use round-nosed or flat-nosed bullets when producing handloads for the tube-magazine Lebel rifles with these cases.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] The older Privi Partizan cases loaded with spire point bullets should only be fired single shot.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] More recently, Privi Partizan manufactured Lebel ammunition with spitzer bullets do incorporate the circular groove at the base, and are safe when stacked in the box-magazine of Berthier rifles and the tubular magazine of Lebel rifles.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] Newer cases with circular groove follow the *balle D* specifications, and shooters may use the magazine for loading.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] 1929 (7.5 French) cartridge was introduced.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/8-50mmr-lebel] This made the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge obsolete, but due to post-World War I financial constraints and political neglect, it was not introduced as a rifle cartridge until the adoption, just before World War II, of the MAS-36 rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In firearms technology, an **action** is the functional mechanism of a breechloading firearm that handles (loads, locks, fires, extracts, and ejects) the ammunition cartridges, or the method by which that mechanism works.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Actions can be categorized in several ways, including single action versus double action, break action versus lever-action, pump-action, bolt-action, among many other types.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The term action can also include short, long, and magnum if it is in reference to the length of the rifle's receiver and the length of the bolt.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The short action rifle usually can accommodate a cartridge length of 2.8 in (71 mm) or smaller.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The long action rifle can accommodate a cartridge of 3.34 in (85 mm), and the magnum action rifle can accommodate cartridges of 3.6 in (91 mm).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Actions are technically not present on muzzleloaders, as all those are single-shot firearms with a closed off breech with the powder and projectile manually loaded from the muzzle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Instead, the muzzleloader ignition mechanism is referred to as the *lock* (e.g. matchlock, wheellock, flintlock, and caplock).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Single-shot actions operate only to ignite a cartridge that is separately set up ("in battery") for firing, and are incapable of moving the cartridge, itself.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] As the name implies, all single-shot firearms (unless they are multi-barreled) can only hold one round of ammunition and need to be manually reloaded after every firing.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Historically, these are the earliest cartridge firearm actions invented.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **dropping block** are actions wherein the breechblock lowers or "drops" into the receiver to open the breech, usually actuated by an underlever.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] There are two principal types of dropping block: the tilting block and the falling block.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In a **tilting block** or **pivoting block** action, the breechblock is hinged on a pin mounted at the rear (in contrast with tilting bolt, which is not hinged).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] When the lever is operated, the block tilts down and forward, exposing the chamber.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The best-known pivoting block designs are the Peabody, the Peabody–Martini, and Ballard actions.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The original Peabody rifles, manufactured by the Providence Tool Company, used a manually cocked side-hammer.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Swiss gunsmith Friedrich Martini developed a pivoting block action by modifying the Peabody, which incorporated a hammerless striker that was cocked by the operating lever with the same single efficient motion that also pivoted the block.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The 1871 Martini–Henry which replaced the "trapdoor" Snider–Enfield was the standard British Army rifle of the later Victorian era, and the Martini is also a popular action for civilian rifles.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Ballard's self-cocking tilting-block action was produced by the Marlin Firearms Company from 1875 and earned a superlative reputation among long-range "Creedmoor" target shooters.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Surviving Marlin Ballards are today highly prized by collectors, especially those mounted in the elaborate Swiss-style Schützen stocks of the day.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In a **falling block** or **sliding block** action, a solid metal breechblock "slides" vertically in grooves cut into the breech of the firearm and actuated by a lever.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Examples of firearms using the falling-block action are the Sharps rifle and Ruger No.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In a **rolling block** action, the breechblock takes the form of a part-cylinder, with a pivot pin through its axis.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The operator rotates or "rolls" the block to open and close the breech; it is a simple, rugged, and reliable design.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Rolling blocks are most often associated with firearms made by Remington in the late 19th century; in the Remington action the hammer serves to lock the breech closed at the moment of firing, and the block in turn prevents the hammer from falling with the breech open.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **hinged block** used in the earliest metallic-cartridge breechloaders designed for general military issue began as conversions of muzzle-loading rifle-muskets.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The upper rear portion of the barrel was filed or milled away and replaced by a hinged breechblock, which opened upward to permit loading.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] An internal angled firing pin allowed the re-use of the rifle's existing side-hammer.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The Allin action made by Springfield Arsenal in the US hinged forward; the Snider–Enfield used by the British opened to the side.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] A **break action** is a type of firearm where the barrel(s) are hinged and can be "broken open" to expose the breech.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Multi-barrel break action firearms are usually subdivided into over-and-under or side-by-side configurations for two barrel configurations or "combination gun" when mixed rifle and shotgun barrels are used.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In **bolt-action** firearms, the opening and closing of the breech is operated by direct manual manipulation of the bolt via a protruding bolt handle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The first general-issue military breechloader was a single-shot bolt action: the paper-cartridge Prussian needle gun of 1841.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] France countered in 1866 with its superior Chassepot rifle, also a paper-cartridge bolt action.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The first metallic-cartridge bolt actions in general military service were the Berdan Type II introduced by Russia in 1870, the Mauser Model 1871, and a modified Chassepot, the Gras rifle of 1874; all these were single-shots.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Single-shot bolt actions in .22 caliber were also widely manufactured as inexpensive "boys' guns" in the earlier 20th century; and there have been a few single-shot bolt-action shotguns, usually in .410 bore.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Today, most top-level smallbore match rifles are single-shot bolt action rifles.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **eccentric screw** action first seen on the M1867 Werndl–Holub and later on the Magnum Research Lone Eagle pistol, the breech closure is a rotating drum with the same axis, but offset from the bore.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] When locked, a firing pin aligns with the primer, the breech is otherwise solid.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] When rotated open, a slot in the drum is exposed for extraction and feeding of a new round.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Though first used on the Werndl-Holub, this action is commonly known as a cannon breech due to its association with the French 75mm Model of 1897 cannon.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The French M1897 was, itself, based on William Hubbell's U.S. patent 149,478.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] A **revolver** is a multi-chamber (but single-barrelled) firearm that houses cartridges in a rotary cylinder which indexes each round into alignment with the bore (with the help of a forcing cone) prior to each shot.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Revolvers are most often handguns; however, examples of revolving rifles, shotguns, and cannons have been made.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The cylinder is most often rotated via linkage to a manually manipulated external hammer, although some revolvers are "double-action" and can use the manual pull of the trigger to drive both the cylinder rotation and hammer cocking.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Some examples of firearms using the revolver principle are the Smith & Wesson Model 3 and Colt Model 1889.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Most bolt-actions utilize a rotating bolt ("turn-pull") design, where the bolt handle must be rotated upwards for unlocking before the bolt can be pulled back to opening the breech and eject any spent cartridge, and must be rotated back down for locking after the bolt closes the breech.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The three predominant rotating bolt-action systems are the Mauser, Lee–Enfield, and Mosin–Nagant systems, with the Mauser system emerging into the mainstream as the most widely used rotating bolt-action design.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] There are also straight pull bolt-action systems that use complex bolt head designs to facilitate locking instead of needing to rotate the bolt handle every time.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In the Mauser-style turn-bolt action, the bolt handle must be rotated upward, pull rearward, pushed forward, and finally rotated back downward into lock.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In a straight pull bolt-action, the bolt can be cycled without rotating, hence reducing the required range of motion by the shooter from four movements to two, with the goal of increasing the rate of fire.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The Ross and Schmidt–Rubin rifles load via stripper clips, albeit of an unusual paperboard and steel design in the Schmidt–Rubin rifle, while the Mannlicher uses en-bloc clips.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The Schmidt–Rubin series, which culminated in the K31, are also known for being among the most accurate military service rifles ever made.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Yet another variant of the straight pull bolt-action, of which the M1895 Lee Navy is an example, is a camming action in which pulling the bolt handle causes the bolt to rock, freeing a stud from the receiver and unlocking the bolt.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In 1993, the German firearms company Blaser, introduced the Blaser R93, a new straight pull bolt-action rifle where locking is achieved by a series of concentric "claws" that protrude/retract from the bolthead, a design that is referred to as *Radialbundverschluss* ("radial connection").
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] As of 2017 the Rifle Shooter magazine listed its successor Blaser R8 as one of the three most popular straight pull bolt-action together with Merkel Helix and Browning Maral.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Some other notable modern straight pull bolt-action rifles are made by Chapuis, Heym, Lynx, Rößler, Strasser, and Steel Action.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In the sport of biathlon, because shooting speed is an important performance factor and semi-automatic guns are illegal for race use, straight pull bolt-actions are quite common, and are used almost exclusively on the Biathlon World Cup.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The first company to make straight pull bolt-actions for .22 caliber was J.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Anschütz; the action is specifically the straight-pull ball bearing-lock action, which features spring-loaded ball bearings on the side of the bolt which lock into a groove inside the bolt's housing.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] With the new design came a new dry-fire method; instead of the bolt being turned up slightly, the action is locked back to catch the firing pin.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In **pump-action** firearms, a sliding grip at the fore-end beneath the barrel is manually operated by the user to eject and chamber cartridges.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Pump actions are predominantly found in shotguns.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Some examples of firearms using the pump-action are the Winchester Model 1912, Remington 870, and Mossberg 500.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **lever-action** firearms, a linked lever is manually operated to eject and chamber cartridges.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Some examples of firearms using lever-action are the Henry Model 1860, Winchester Model 1876, and Marlin Model 1894.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **bolt release** or **lever release** action is a hybrid repeating action that uses the physical manipulation of a bolt release lever/button to complete the cartridge chambering process.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] However, after moving rearwards the bolt is stopped by a bolt catch and will not move back into battery position and chamber the new round, until the user manually disengages the catch by depressing a release lever/button.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Due to the fact that the action can not complete its loading cycle without manual input from the user, it is technically a manually operated action rather than a self-loading one.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In 2020, CZ also introduced CZ 515, a bolt-release modified version of the CZ 512, to the Australian market via its importer Winchester Australia.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The Turkish manufacturer Pardus Arms also produces the 12 gauge-caliber BRS17 shotgun, which uses a bolt release button on the back of the receiver to chamber rounds before firing.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **blowback operation** is a system in which semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms operate through the energy created by combustion in the chamber and bore acting directly on the bolt face through the cartridge.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In blowback operation the bolt is not locked to the chamber, relying only on spring pressure and inertia from the weight of the bolt to keep the action from opening too quickly.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Blowback operation is used for low-powered cartridges due to the weight of the bolt required.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Delayed blowback actions use some mechanism to slow down rearward travel of the bolt, allowing this action to handle more powerful ammunition and/or reduced weight of the bolt.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **blow-forward** operation uses a fixed breech and moving barrel that is forced forward relative to the breech by the friction of the projectile against the bore as well as the breech recoiling away from the barrel.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The barrel is spring loaded and returns automatically to chamber a fresh round from the magazine.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] Examples of this action are the Steyr Mannlicher M1894, Hino Komuro M1908 Pistol and the Schwarzlose Model 1908.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **recoil operation** is a type of locked-breech action used in semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] It also uses energy from the combustion in the chamber acting directly on the bolt through the cartridge head, but in this case the firearm has a reciprocating barrel and breech assembly, combined with a bolt that locks to the breech.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The breech remains locked as the bolt and barrel travel rearward together for some distance, allowing pressure in the chamber to drop to a safe level before the breech is opened.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] The **gas operation** is a system of operation mechanism used to provide energy to semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] In gas-operation, a portion of high pressure gas from the cartridge being fired is tapped through a hole in the barrel and diverted to operate the action.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] A fourth type, now considered obsolete and ineffective, are those systems based on the Bang rifle that utilize a muzzle cap to capture gas after the bullet has left the barrel.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/action-firearms] While this system is successful in boosting the operating power of recoil operated guns, it is insufficient and too susceptible to fouling for use as the primary operating system.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Anti-personnel shells are designed to fragment into many pieces and can affect a large area.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Armor-piercing rounds are specially hardened to penetrate armor, while smoke ammunition creates a fog that screens people from view.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] More generic ammunition (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) can often be modified slightly to achieve a more specific effect (e.g., tracer, incendiary), whilst larger explosive rounds can be altered by using different fuzes.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The term *fuze* refers to the detonator of an explosive round or shell.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The spelling is different in British English and American English (fuse/fuze respectively), and they are unrelated to a fuse (electrical).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] A fuse was earlier used to ignite the propellant (e.g., such as on a firework) until the advent of more reliable systems, such as the primer or igniter that is used in most modern ammunition.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The fuze of a weapon can be used to alter how the ammunition works.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] These allow a single ammunition type to be altered to suit the situation it is required for.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] There are many fuze designs, ranging from simple mechanical to complex radar- and barometric-based systems.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Fuzes are typically armed by the acceleration force of firing the projectile and are armed several meters after clearing the weapon's bore.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] This helps to ensure the ammunition is safer to handle when loading into the weapon and reduces the chance of the detonator firing before the ammunition has cleared the weapon.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The propellant is the component of ammunition that is activated inside the weapon and provides the kinetic energy required to move the projectile from the weapon to the target.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] In recent years, compressed gas, magnetic energy, and electrical energy have been used as propellants.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Until the 20th century, gunpowder was the most common propellant in ammunition.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] However, it has since been replaced by a wide range of fast-burning compounds that are more reliable and efficient.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The propellant charge is distinct from the projectile charge, which is activated by the fuze, which causes the ammunition effect (e.g., the exploding of an artillery round).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The cartridge is the container that holds the projectile and propellant.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Not all ammunition types have a cartridge case.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] In its place, a wide range of materials can be used to contain the explosives and parts.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] With some large weapons, the ammunition components are stored separately until loaded into the weapon system for firing.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] With small arms, caseless ammunition can reduce the weight and cost of ammunition and simplify the firing process, increasing the firing rate, but the technology is still maturing and has functional issues.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The projectile is the part of the ammunition that leaves the weapon and affects the target.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] This effect is usually either kinetic (e.g., as with a standard bullet) or explosive.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] An ammunition dump is a military facility for storing live ammunition and explosives to be distributed and used at a later date.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Such a storage facility is extremely hazardous, with a high risk of accidents during unloading, packing, and transferring the ammunition.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] In the event of a fire or explosion, the site and its surrounding area are immediately evacuated, and the stored ammunition is left to detonate completely, with limited firefighting attempts from a safe distance.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] In large facilities, there may be a flooding system to extinguish a fire or prevent an explosion automatically.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Typically, an ammunition dump will have a large buffer zone surrounding it to avoid casualties in the event of an accident.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] There will also be perimeter security measures in place to prevent unauthorized personnel from accessing the area and to guard against potential threats from enemy forces.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] A magazine is a place where a quantity of ammunition or other explosive material is stored temporarily before being used.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The term may be used for a facility that stores large quantities of ammunition, although this is normally referred to as an ammunition dump.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Magazines are typically located in the field for quick access when engaging the enemy.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The ammunition storage area on a warship is referred to as the "ship's magazine".
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] On a smaller scale, magazine is also the name given to the ammunition storage and feeding device of a repeating firearm.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Gunpowder must be stored in a dry place (stable room temperature) to keep it usable for at least 10 years.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] It is also recommended to avoid hot places, because friction or heat might ignite a spark and cause an explosion.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The standard weapon of a modern soldier is an assault rifle, which, like other small arms, uses cartridge ammunition sized for the weapon.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Ammunition is carried on the person in box magazines specific to the weapon, ammunition boxes, pouches, or bandoliers.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The amount of ammunition carried depends on the soldier's strength, the expected action required, and the ammunition's ability to move through the logistical chain to replenish the supply.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] A soldier may also carry a smaller amount of specialized ammunition for heavier weapons, such as machine guns and mortars, thereby spreading the burden of squad weapons among many people.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Too little ammunition threatens the mission, while too much limits the soldier's mobility and also threatens the mission.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] A shell is a payload-carrying projectile which, as opposed to a shot, contains explosives or other fillings, in use since the 19th century.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Artillery shells are ammunition that is designed to be fired from artillery, which has an effect over long distances, usually indirectly (i.e., out of sight of the target).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] There are many different types of artillery ammunition, but they are usually high-explosive and designed to shatter into fragments on impact to maximize damage.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The fuze on an artillery shell can alter how it explodes or behaves, giving it a more specialized effect.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Common types of artillery ammunition include high explosive, smoke, illumination, and practice rounds.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Some artillery rounds are designed as cluster munitions.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Artillery ammunition will almost always include a projectile (the only exception being demonstration or blank rounds), fuze, and propellant of some form.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] When a cartridge case is not used, another method of containing the propellant bags is used, usually in a breech-loading weapon; see Breechloader.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Tank ammunition was developed in World War I as tanks first appeared on the battlefield.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The development of shaped charges has had a significant impact on anti-tank ammunition design, now common in both tank-fired ammunition and in anti-tank missiles, including anti-tank guided missiles.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Naval weapons were originally the same as many land-based weapons, but the ammunition was designed for specific use, such as a solid shot designed to hole an enemy ship and chain-shot to cut rigging and sails.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Modern naval engagements have occurred over far longer distances than historic battles, so as ship armor has increased in strength and thickness, the ammunition to defeat it has also changed.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Naval ammunition is now designed to reach very high velocities (to improve its armor-piercing abilities) and may have specialized fuzes to defeat specific types of vessels.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] However, due to the extended ranges at which modern naval combat may occur, guided missiles have largely supplanted guns and shells.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] With every successive improvement in military arms, a corresponding change has occurred in the method of supplying ammunition in the required quantities.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] As soon as projectiles were required (such as javelins and arrows), there needed to be a method of replenishment.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] When non-specialized, interchangeable, or recoverable ammunition was used (e.g., arrows), it was possible to pick up spent arrows (both friendly and enemy) and reuse them.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] However, with the advent of explosive or non-recoverable ammunition, this was no longer possible, and new ammunition supplies would be needed.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The weight of ammunition required, particularly for artillery shells, can be considerable, necessitating extra time to replenish supplies.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] In modern times, there has been an increase in the standardization of many ammunition types among allies (e.g., the NATO Standardization Agreement) that has enabled the sharing of ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO).
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] As of 2013, lead-based ammunition production is the second-largest annual use of lead in the US, accounting for over 60,000 metric tons consumed in 2012.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in a carcass or body that was never retrieved can enter environmental systems and become toxic to wildlife.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] The US military has experimented with replacing lead with copper as a slug in their green bullets which reduces the dangers posed by lead in the environment as a result of artillery.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Since 2010, this has eliminated over 2000 tons of lead in waste streams.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Hunters are also encouraged to use monolithic bullets, which exclude any lead content.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/ammunition] Unexploded ammunition can remain active for a very long time and poses a significant threat to both humans and the environment.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The **Fusil Modèle 1874** or **Gras** was the French Army's primary service rifle from 1874 to 1886.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] Designed by Colonel Basile Gras, the Gras was a metallic cartridge adaptation of the single-shot, breech-loading, black powder Chassepot rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] It was developed from 1872 to 1874 as a response to the German adoption of the Mauser Model 1871 metallic cartridge rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] Modified in 1880 as the **M80** with an improved breechblock and in 1914 as the **M14** to accommodate the 8×50mmR Lebel smokeless powder cartridge, the Gras was replaced as the standard-issue service rifle by the Lebel in 1886.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] Converted from the Chassepot, the Gras was in 11 mm (0.43 in) caliber and used black powder centerfire metallic cartridges with a 385 gr (24.9 g; 0.88 oz) bullet over a 78 gr (5.1 g; 0.18 oz) charge.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] It was a robust and hard-hitting single-shot weapon.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] Additionally it had a triangular-shaped Model 1874 "Gras" sword bayonet.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The Gras rifle was replaced from 1886 by the Lebel rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The Gras was manufactured in response to the development of the Boxer cartridge in 1866, and the British 1870 Martini–Henry rifle which used it.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] Those were soon emulated by the Germans with the 1871 Mauser.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The French Army set up a study group in September 1871 that chose the metallic over the paper cartridge.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] A second study group in 1873 looked at various metallic cartridge adaptations.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] Colonel Gras proposed a modification of the Chassepot to accept metal cartridges and on 7 July 1874, the French Army chose his design over the M1871 Beaumont rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The Hellenic Army adopted the Gras in 1877, and it was used in all conflicts until the Second World War.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] It became the favourite weapon of Greek guerrilla fighters, from the various revolts against the Ottoman Empire to the resistance against the Axis, acquiring legendary status.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The name entered the Greek language, and *grades* (γκράδες) was a term colloquially applied to all rifles during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] It was manufactured by Manufacture d'armes de Saint-Étienne, one of several government-owned arms factories in France.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] However most of the Gras rifles (60,000) used by the Hellenic military were manufactured under licence by Steyr in Austria.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The Gras rifle was partly the inspiration for the development of the Japanese Murata rifle, Japan's first locally made service rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] It was also among the rifles copied in the arms industry of the Wassoulou Empire in the 1880s and 90s.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] According to Vietnamese historian Phạm Văn Sơn, Cao Thắng, a leader of the Cần Vương movement, managed to copy the design of a "French 1874-type rapid-firing rifle", yet this variation has a limited range and the absence of a rifled barrel.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] In 1915, 450,000 Gras rifles were sent to the Russian Empire.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] After 1918, Mle 1874 rifles were exported to Yugoslavia, Poland and Greece.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] In 1914, the French Army modified 146,000 rifles to fire 8 mm Lebel by using the barrel of a Lebel or Berthier rifle.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] In 1940, after the French defeat, although receiving the designation **Gewehr 361(f)**, most of these rifles were destroyed by the German occupiers.
[src:fusil-gras-mle-1874/fusil-gras-mle-1874] The period 1932-1939 Greece manufactured the M1939 bayonet, it was a modification of the Gras Model 1874 bayonet and was used by Greek soldiers in World War II.
